On day three, I learnt how to secure remote access to network devices using Telnet and SSH. The lesson focused on protecting network devices from unauthorized access and ensuring secure remote management of switches.

Topics Covered and What I Learnt
1. Telnet Operation

I learnt how Telnet works as a remote access protocol that allows administrators to manage network devices over a network connection. I understood that:

Telnet sends data in plain text
Usernames and passwords are not encrypted
It is less secure for modern networks

This helped me understand why Telnet is mainly used in controlled or testing environments.

2. SSH Operation

I learnt about Secure Shell (SSH), which provides encrypted remote access to network devices. I understood that SSH:

Encrypts usernames, passwords, and data
Protects communication from attackers
Provides secure remote management

I learnt why SSH is preferred over Telnet in real-world networking environments.

3. Verify the Switch Supports SSH

I learnt how to check whether a switch supports SSH functionality. This involved verifying:

IOS version compatibility
Device capabilities
Existing configurations required for SSH

This step is important before configuring secure remote access.

4. Configure SSH

I practised configuring SSH on a switch. During the configuration process, I learnt how to:

Set the hostname
Configure the domain name
Generate RSA encryption keys
Create local usernames and passwords
Enable SSH on VTY lines

This gave me practical experience in securing network devices.

5. Verify SSH is Operational

I learnt how to test and verify whether SSH was working properly. I used commands to:

Check SSH status
Confirm successful remote login
Verify encrypted remote connections

This helped me understand how to confirm that a switch is securely accessible.

6. Packet Tracer – Configure SSH

Finally, I completed a Packet Tracer lab where I configured SSH on a switch in a simulated network environment. The practical exercise allowed me to apply all the concepts learnt during the lesson and strengthened my confidence in configuring secure remote access on network devices.
